<section xml:id="subsec-volume-of-cylinders" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>(*) Volume of Cylinders</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.0 Measurements and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.8 Volume
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
        </introduction>
        <ul>
            <li>Determine the volume of composite solids</li>
            <li>Explore the use of the surface area and volume of solids in real-life situations</li>
        </ul>
    </objectives>
        <activity>
        <p>
            <term>Work in groups:</term>
        </p>
        <p>
            <term>Materials Needed:</term> A cylinder-shaped container (e.g., a can or a water bottle), a measuring tape, water, and a measuring cup.
        </p>
        <p>
            <term>Instruction:</term>
        </p>
        <p>
            Form groups of <m>2-3</m> students.
        </p>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Find the radius and height of the cylinder-shaped container (i.e. a can) using the measuring tape, in centimeters.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Pour water to fill the cylinder.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Transfer the water from the cylinder to the measuring cup and record the volume of water in milliliters (mL).
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Calculate the volume of the cylinder using the formula <m>V = \pi r^2 h</m>, where <m>r</m> is the radius and <m>h</m> is the height. Use <m>\pi = 3.14</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Compare your calculated volume with milliliters you measured (mL). Discuss any differences and possible reasons for them.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </activity>
    <insight>
        <p>
            The volume of a cylinder can be calculated using the formula <md>V = \pi r^2 h</md>, where <m>r</m> is the radius of the circular base and <m>h</m> is the height of the cylinder. 
        </p>
        <p> This formula is just a special case of the volume formula for prisms (<m> V = Fh</m>), since the area of a circular base is given by <m>F = \pi r^2</m>.
        </p>
    </insight>
        <example xml:id="auto_kq0lvxhp">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_hp2uyvm3">
                    The cylinder below has a radius of 4 cm and a height of 10 cm. Use <m>\pi = 3.142</m>
                </p>
                 <image width="45%">
        <shortdescription>Cylindrical prism</shortdescription>
     <latex-image label="volume-of-a-cylinder-exercise-one">
        \begin{tikzpicture}[rotate=90]
            % Draw the top ellipse
            \draw (0,4) ellipse (1.5 and 0.5);

            % Draw the vertical sides of the cylinder (height doubled)
            \draw (-1.5,4) -- (-1.5,0);
            \draw (1.5,4) -- (1.5,0);
             \draw[dashed] (1.5,4) --(0,4);
             \node at (0.8,4.2) {4 cm};
             \draw[dashed] (0,0) --(0,4);
             \node at (0.2,2.2) {10 cm};
            % Draw the bottom ellipse (partially hidden)
            \draw[thick] (0,0) ellipse (1.5 and 0.5); % Shaded bottom base
            \draw[dashed] (0,0) ellipse (1.5 and 0.5);  % Dashed for hidden portion
        \end{tikzpicture}
     </latex-image>
    </image>
                <p xml:id="auto_ivk90ho4">
                    <md>
                        <mrow> V \amp = \text{Base Area }\times h  </mrow>
                        <mrow> V \amp = \pi r^2 \times h</mrow>
                        <mrow> \amp = 3.142 \times (4)^2 \, \text{cm} \times 10\, \text{cm}</mrow>
                        <mrow> \amp = 502.65\, \text{cm}^3</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </example> 
        <example xml:id="auto_jh0p8qva">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_8j54e6gp">
                    A pipe has a radius of 3 cm and a height of 15 cm. Find the volume of the pipe.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p xml:id="auto_11wdvqvt">
                    <md>
                        <mrow> V \amp = \text{Base Area} \times h </mrow>
                        <mrow> V \amp = \pi r^2 \times h</mrow>
                        <mrow> \amp = 3.142 \times (3)^2 \, \text{cm} \times 15\, \text{cm}</mrow>
                        <mrow> \amp = 424.12\, \text{cm}^3</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>
            <example xml:id="auto_0t4ay4zp">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_t5trlgqs">
            Find the volume of the following cylinder using <m>\pi = 3.142</m>. Leave your answer  (correct to 2 decimal place): 
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_dzokcsdc">
                Step 1: Find the area of the base
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_k48ob82t">
                <md>
                    <mrow>\text {area of circle } = \amp \pi r^2 </mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp \pi(8)^2</mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp \pi 64\,\text{cm}^2</mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp 3,142  \times 64\,\text{cm}^2 </mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp 201.088 \,\text{cm}^2 </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_1vmmscs8">
            Step 2: Multiply the area of the base by the height of the solid to find the volume  
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_8uwcwt5y">
                <md>
                <mrow> \text{Volume} = \amp \text{Base area} \times \text{height}</mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp \pi r^2 \times h  </mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp201.088 \, \text{cm}^2 \times 20\, \text{cm} </mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp 4021.76 \, \text{cm}^3 </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_6hljpkqj">
            The volume of the cylinder is <m>4021.76 \, \text{cm}^3 </m>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
        <example xml:id="auto_hfmox9om">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_dm9jba4g">
                    Mueni's water tank has a radius of 7 m and a height of 20 m. Find the capacity of the water tank in litres.
                </p>
            </statement>

            <solution>
                <p xml:id="auto_occ9zft9">
                 <md>
                        <mrow> V \amp = \text{Base Area} \times h  </mrow>
                        <mrow> V \amp = \pi r^2 \times h</mrow>
                        <mrow> \amp = \frac{22}{7} \times (7)^2\, \text{m} \times 20 \, \text{m}</mrow>
                        <mrow> \amp = 3080\, \text{m}^3</mrow>
                    </md>   
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_bmvqlgsi">
                    To convert from <m>m^3 </m> to litres we multiply by <m>1000 \, L/\text{m}^3</m>
                    <md>
                        <mrow> 1 \text{litre} \amp = 1000\, \text{m}^3 </mrow>
                        <mrow>  \amp = 3080\, \text{m}^3 \times 1000\, \text{L/m}^3</mrow>
                        <mrow> \amp = 3,080,000 \, \text{ litres}</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_xdjl4kas">
                    
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example> 
                    <exercise  label="ex-calculating-the-volume-of-a-cylinder">
                <stack label="stk-calculating-the-volume-of-a-cylinder" source="stack/top/2-0-Measurement-Geometry/2-7-Surface-Area-and-Volume-of-Solids/2-7-13-Volume-of-a-Cylinder/Calculating-the-Volume-of-a-Cylinder.xml" />
            </exercise>
                

            <exercise  label="ex-calculating-the-volume-of-material-in-a-hollow-cylinder">
                <stack label="stk-calculating-the-volume-of-material-in-a-hollow-cylinder" source="stack/top/2-0-Measurement-Geometry/2-7-Surface-Area-and-Volume-of-Solids/2-7-13-Volume-of-a-Cylinder/Calculating-the-Volume-of-Material-in-a-Hollow-Cylinder.xml" />
            </exercise>
    <exercises>
        <p>
            Unless otherwise stated, use <m>\pi = 3.14</m> in all calculations.
        </p> 
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Alongside is a cross-sectional view of an open cylinder that has a radius of 7 cm and a height of 10 cm. Find its volume.
                </p>
                <image width="40%">
            <latex-image label="cylinder5-two">
                \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.2, rotate=90] % Rotated 90 degrees to lie horizontally
                    % Define dimensions
                    \def\diameter{24} % Diameter of the cylinder
                    \def\radius{12}   % Radius of the cylinder (half of diameter)
                    \def\height{30}   % Length of the cylinder (previously height)

                    % Draw and fill the curved surface with green
                    \fill[pink] (-\radius,0) -- (-\radius,-\height)
                    arc (180:360:\radius cm and 2cm)
                    -- (\radius,0)
                    arc (0:180:\radius cm and 2cm);

                    % Fill the front and back cross-sections with white
                    \fill[pink] (-\radius,0) arc (180:360:\radius cm and 2cm)
                    arc (0:180:\radius cm and 2cm);
                                
                    \fill[white] (-\radius,-\height) arc (180:360:\radius cm and 2cm)
                    arc (0:180:\radius cm and 2cm);

                    % Draw the front ellipse
                    \draw[thick,magenta] (-\radius,0) arc (180:360:\radius cm and 2cm);
                    \draw[ thick,magenta] (\radius,0) arc (0:180:\radius cm and 2cm);

                    % Draw the back ellipse
                    \draw[thick,magenta] (-\radius,-\height) arc (180:360:\radius cm and 2cm);
                    \draw[ thick,magenta] (\radius,-\height) arc (0:180:\radius cm and 2cm);

                    % Draw the sides
                    \draw[thick,] (-\radius,0) -- (-\radius,-\height);
                    \draw[thick,magenta] (\radius,0) -- (\radius,-\height);

                    % Label Diameter (Vertical since cylinder is lying down)
                    \draw[&lt;-&gt;, black, thick] (-\radius, 4) -- (\radius, 4)
                    node[midway, above, font=\bfseries, black, rotate=-90] {14 cm};

                    % Label Length (formerly height, now horizontal)
                    \draw[&lt;-&gt;, black, thick] (\radius + 2, 0) -- (\radius + 2, -\height)
                    node[midway, left, font=\bfseries, black, rotate=-90] {10 cm};
                \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
            </image>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    Use <m>V=\pi r^2 h</m> with <m>r=7\,\text{cm}</m> and <m>h=10\,\text{cm}</m>.
                </p>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow> V \amp = \pi \times 7^2 \times 10 </mrow>
                        <mrow> \amp = \pi \times 49 \times 10 </mrow>
                        <mrow> \amp = 490\pi\,\text{cm}^3 </mrow>
                        <mrow> \amp \approx 3.14 \times 490 = 1538.6\,\text{cm}^3 </mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Calculate the volume of a cylinder with radius <m>6\,\text{cm}</m> and height <m>10\,\text{cm}</m>. (Use <m>\pi=3.14</m>.)
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    Using <m>V=\pi r^2 h</m> we have
                </p>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow> V\amp=3.14\times 6^2 \times 10</mrow>
                        <mrow> \amp=3.14\times 36 \times 10</mrow>
                        <mrow> \amp=1130.4\,\text{cm}^3</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A cylinder has diameter <m>10\,\text{cm}</m> and height <m>12\,\text{cm}</m>. Find its volume in terms of <m>\pi</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    The radius is <m>r=\tfrac{10}{2}=5\,\text{cm}</m>. Using <m>V=\pi r^2 h</m>:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow> V\amp=\pi\times 5^2 \times 12</mrow>
                        <mrow> \amp=\pi \times 25 \times 12</mrow>
                        <mrow> \amp=300\pi\,\text{cm}^3</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
        <p xml:id="auto_mfbnnrha">
            A cylinder has a volume of <m>1,570 \text{cm}^3</m> and a diameter of 30 cm.
          Find its height.
        </p>
        <image width="40%">
            <latex-image label="cylinder-five-two">
                \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.2, rotate=90] % Rotated 90 degrees to lie horizontally
                      % Define dimensions
                    \def\diameter{24} % Diameter of the cylinder
                    \def\radius{12}   % Radius of the cylinder (half of diameter)
                    \def\height{30}   % Length of the cylinder (previously height)

                    % Draw and fill the curved surface with green
                    \draw[thick] (-\radius,0) -- (-\radius,-\height)
                    arc (180:360:\radius cm and 2cm)
                    -- (\radius,0)
                    arc (0:180:\radius cm and 2cm);

                    % Fill the front and back cross-sections with white
                    \draw[thick] (-\radius,0) arc (180:360:\radius cm and 2cm)
                    arc (0:180:\radius cm and 2cm);
                                
                    \fill[white] (-\radius,-\height) arc (180:360:\radius cm and 2cm)
                    arc (0:180:\radius cm and 2cm);

                    % Draw the front ellipse
                    \draw[thick] (-\radius,0) arc (180:360:\radius cm and 2cm);
                    \draw[ thick] (\radius,0) arc (0:180:\radius cm and 2cm);

                    % Draw the back ellipse
                    \draw[thick] (-\radius,-\height) arc (180:360:\radius cm and 2cm);
                    \draw[ thick] (\radius,-\height) arc (0:180:\radius cm and 2cm);

                    % Draw the sides
                    \draw[thick,] (-\radius,0) -- (-\radius,-\height);
                    \draw[thick] (\radius,0) -- (\radius,-\height);

                    % Label Diameter (Vertical since cylinder is lying down)
                    \draw[&lt;-&gt;, blue, thick] (-\radius, 4) -- (\radius, 4)
                    node[midway, above, font=\bfseries, blue, rotate=-90] {30 cm};

                    % Label Length (formerly height, now horizontal)
                    \draw[&lt;-&gt;, blue, thick] (\radius + 2, 0) -- (\radius + 2, -\height)
                    node[midway, left, font=\bfseries, blue, rotate=-90] {h cm};
                \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
            
                
            </image>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    Radius <m>r=\tfrac{30}{2}=15\,\text{cm}</m>. Using <m>V=\pi r^2 h</m> we get
                </p>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow> h\amp=\dfrac{V}{\pi r^2} = \dfrac{1570}{3.14\times 15^2}</mrow>
                        <mrow> \amp=\dfrac{1570}{706.5}</mrow>
                        <mrow> \amp\approx 2.22\,\text{cm}</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>   

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A cylindrical water tank has a radius of 2 m and a height of 5 m. How many liters of water can it hold when full? (Use <m>\pi = 3.14</m>, remember that 1 cubic meter = 1000 liters)
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    Using <m>V=\pi r^2 h</m> we have
                </p>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow> V \amp = \pi r^2 h </mrow>
                        <mrow> \amp = 3.14 \times (2)^2\, \text{m} \times 5\, \text{m} </mrow>
                        <mrow> \amp = 3.14 \times 4 \times 5\, \text{m}^3 </mrow>
                        <mrow> \amp = 62.8\, \text{m}^3 </mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                    To convert from <m>\text{m}^3</m> to litres we multiply by <m>1000\,\text{L/m}^3</m>.
                </p>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow> V = 62.8\, \text{m}^3 \times 1000\, \text{L/m}^3 </mrow>
                        <mrow> \amp = 62,800\, \text{litres} </mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    If the radius of a cylinder is doubled while keeping the height the same, by what factor does the volume increase?
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    Let the original radius be <m>r</m> and height <m>h</m>. Original volume: <m>V=\pi r^2 h</m>.
                </p>
                <p>
                    If radius is doubled (<m>r'=2r</m>) then
                </p>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow> V' \amp = \pi (2r)^2 h = \pi \times 4r^2 h = 4\pi r^2 h </mrow>
                        <mrow> \amp = 4V </mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Therefore the volume increases by a factor of <m>4</m>.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <title>A Harder Exercise</title>
            <statement>
                <p> A hollow cylindrical pipe has an outer radius of 8 cm, an inner radius of 6 cm, and a length of 100 cm. Find the volume of material used to make the pipe.  
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    The volume of material is the volume of the outer cylinder minus the inner cylinder: <m>V=\pi(R^2-r^2)h</m>.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Here <m>R=8\,\text{cm}</m>, <m>r=6\,\text{cm}</m> and <m>h=100\,\text{cm}</m>. So
                </p>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow> V \amp = \pi(8^2-6^2)\times 100</mrow>
                        <mrow> \amp = \pi(64-36)\times 100</mrow>
                        <mrow> \amp = \pi\times 28 \times 100</mrow>
                        <mrow> \amp = 2800\pi\,\text{cm}^3</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Using <m>\pi=3.14</m> (unless otherwise stated) gives
                </p>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow> V \amp \approx 3.14 \times 2800 = 8792\,\text{cm}^3 </mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>
    </exercises>
                
</section>